Architecture Overview
This is a client-orchestrated, sequential processing architecture built in Angular, where the UI layer acts as the primary workflow coordinator rather than delegating batch orchestration to the backend.

Structural Layout — Three-Tab Presentation Layer
The UI is divided into three functionally distinct sections, each representing a different stage of the content processing lifecycle:
Upload & Generate Tab is the entry point where users introduce VTT/SRT files into the system and trigger immediate inference. History Tab serves as the control plane for revisiting, reconfiguring, and re-running inference on previously uploaded files. Workspace Tab is the read-only output surface where completed results — summaries, keywords, and assessment questions — are surfaced for consumption.

Core Architectural Patterns
1. Client-Orchestrated Sequential File Upload
Rather than sending a batch payload to the backend, the Angular layer owns the upload queue and enforces a strict sequential processing discipline:
[File Queue: F1, F2, F3]
      │
      ▼
  Upload F1 ──► Backend API
      │              │
      │         (processing)
      │              │
      ◄──────── Response OK
      │
  Upload F2 ──► Backend API
      │
     ...
This is a promise-chaining / observable-pipeline pattern — each upload is only triggered after the previous one resolves successfully. In Angular, this is typically implemented using RxJS concatMap, which naturally serialises emissions from a file array into sequential HTTP calls, as opposed to mergeMap which would parallelise them.
The rationale for this design is usually to avoid backend resource contention, respect rate limits, or maintain ordering guarantees — especially important when downstream processing (e.g. AI inference) is compute-heavy.
2. Single vs. Multi-File Inference Branching (History Tab)
The History Tab introduces a conditional dispatch pattern:
User Selection
      │
      ├─── Single File ──► Single Inference API Call
      │                         │
      │                    (one payload, one response)
      │
      └─── Multiple Files ──► Multi-File Inference API Call
                                    │
                               (batch payload or
                                parallel dispatch)
The UI branches into two distinct API invocation strategies based on selection cardinality. This keeps the backend contracts clean — a single-file endpoint can be optimised for low-latency response, while the multi-file endpoint can be designed for throughput or async handling.
3. Optional Prompt Overrides (History Tab)
The History Tab supports parameterised re-inference — users can optionally override the Summary Prompt and Assessment Question Prompt before triggering generation. This means the API call carries a payload that conditionally includes prompt overrides, and the backend falls back to defaults when they are absent. This is a partial configuration injection pattern.
